<html>
<body>

<center>
<b>CREATE SLR QUICK-LOOK RESIDUAL STATISTICS</b>
<p>Program: QLRSUM
</center>
<hr width="100%">

<a name="ENVIRONMENT"   default="%% %%"></a>
<a name="CAMPAIGN"      default=""></a>
<a name="SESSION_TABLE" default="SESSIONS"></a>
<a name="YR4_INFO"      default="$Y+0"></a>
<a name="SES_INFO"      default="$S+0"></a>
<a name="USR_INFO"      default="${USER}"></a>

<p><b>GENERAL DESCRIPTION</b>
<p>
This program does a quick look residual analysis and creates a report.
The report may be written to a special summary file, which is suited to be
sent as slrmail (mail list from the ILRS).

<p><hr>

<p><b>QLRSUM 1: Filenames</b>

<a name="SHOWGEN" default="1"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL FILES</b>
<p><b>Show all general files:</b>
Check this box to get a list of the general input files used by this program
as well as the currently active campaign, session, and session table.

<br><br>

<a name="RESFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>INPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Residual files:</b>
Select the SLR residual files from which a summary should be made.
The residual files result from <a href="PGMLST.HLP#GPSEST">GPSEST</a> runs.

<a name="STDORB" default=""></a>
<p><b>Standard orbit files:</b>
Select the corresponding standard orbit files containing orbits for the
satellites to be analysed.

<a name="SKLFIL" default="SLRMAIL"></a>
<p><b>Skeleton file for slrmail:</b>
This skeleton file is used to create a summary file, that may be sent as slrmail.

<a name="CRDFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>Station coordinates:</b>
Select the file with the SLR station coordinates.

<a name="POLE" default=""></a>
<p><b>ERP file:</b>
Select the pole file, which has been used in the SLR processing and which
is consistent with the standard orbits.

<br><br>

<a name="SUMFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>OUTPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Summary file for slrmail:</b>
Specify the name of a summary file, which may be sent as slrmail.

<a name="ALLFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>Detailed residual output:</b>
Specify the name of the file with the detailed residual output.

<a name="PLTFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>Detailed residual output for graphic tools:</b>
A plot-file with the residuals may be created (to be used to display
the residuals graphically with appropriate tools, e.g., gnuplot).

<a name="EDITRS" default=""></a>
<p><b>Edit file</b> <b>(observations during shadow passage):</b>
Observations during phases when the satellite is in the Earth's shadow
will be written to this file.
<br>
It may later be used by the program <a href="PGMLST.HLP#SATMRK">SATMRK</a>
to mark these observations.

<a name="EDTFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>Edit file</b> <b>(outlier detection; too few observations):</b>
Observations that are detected as outlier according to the program settings
made in panel "QLRSUM 3: Outlier detection" will be written to this file.
<br>
It may later be used by the program SATMRK to mark these observations.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.EDT">Example</a> for an editing file.

<br><br>

<a name="SYSODEF" default="1"></a>
<a name="SYSOUT"  default="QLRSUM"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL OUTPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Program output:</b>
You can choose to have the program output written to a separate file for each
program run (checkbox marked), or specify a common name for all program runs.
<br>
If you mark the checkbox, the filename will correspond to the program name
with an extension containing a counter (Lnn), which is automatically
incremented for each program run. If the counter reaches the maximum value, it
is automatically reset, and existing files will be overwritten.
The maximum value can be set in
<b>Menu &gt; Configure &gt; Program Names</b>, option "Maximum program output
file number".
<br>
If the checkbox is unmarked, you have to specify a name for the program
output file. This allows to characterize the program run, e.g., by using the
day and year (<tt>$YD+0</tt>) in the filename.

<a name="ERRMRG" default="0"></a>
<a name="SYSERR" default="ERROR"></a>
<p><b>Error messages:</b>
You can choose to have error messages written into the program's output
file (see above), or to specify a separate file to which error messages are
written.

<p><hr>

<p><b>QLRSUM 1.1: General Files</b>

<a name="CONST" default="CONST."></a>
<p><b>GENERAL INPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>General constants:</b>
This file contains all the physical and astronomical constants used
in the Bernese GNSS Software. Most probably you will never have to
modify this file.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/CONST.">CONST.</a>

<a name="SUBMOD" default="IERS2010XY"></a>
<p><b>Subdaily pole model:</b>
This file contains the parameters for the subdaily pole model. It
has to be identical to the one used for the computation of the
standard orbit.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/IERS2010XY.SUB">$X/GEN/IERS2010XY.SUB</a>

<a name="NUTMOD" default="IAU2000R06"></a>
<p><b>Nutation model:</b>
This file contains the parameters for the nutation model. It
has to be identical to the one used for the computation of the
standard orbit.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/IAU2000R06.NUT">$X/GEN/IAU2000R06.NUT</a>

<a name="SATELL" default="SATELLIT.I08"></a>
<p><b>Satellite information:</b>
This file contains general information on GNSS (and LEO/GEO/SLR)
satellites.  For the session to be processed, each satellite has to appear
once in this file within a corresponding time window.

<p><i>Note:</i>
The file $X/GEN/SATELLIT.I08 is maintained by AIUB/CODE.
It includes a complete history concerning the GPS satellite constellation
(and newly launched satellites are regularly added).
You can get the latest version of this file from the
<a href="/$X/DOC/README_AIUB_AFTP.TXT">anonymous ftp</a> account of AIUB.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/SATELLIT.I08">SATELLIT.I08</a>

<a name="GPSUTC" default="GPSUTC."></a>
<p><b>GPS-UTC seconds:</b>
Specify the file with GPS-UTC values here. You have to update this file
each time a leap second is introduced. The GPS-UTC values are needed for
this program, because the time argument in the summary file is in UTC time.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/GPSUTC.">$X/GEN/GPSUTC.</a>

<a name="ABBREV" default="ABBREV"></a>
<p><b>Abbreviation table:</b>
This file contains a station name abbreviation table containing
<nobr>4-character</nobr> and <nobr>2-character</nobr> abbreviations for a
list of station names.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.ABB">Example</a>

<a name="STAINFO" default=""></a>
<p><b>Station information:</b>
This file contains station specific information. QLRSUM only needs the
information on the SLR stations.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMP_SLR.STA">Example</a>

<p><hr>

<p><b>QLRSUM 2: Input Options</b>

<a name="TITLE" default=""></a>
<p><b>TITLE</b>
<p>
This title line will be printed as header comment into the program output
to document the program run. The title should characterize the program run by,
e.g., giving the most important options used and the session.

<br><br>

<a name="SATLST" default="%%"></a>
<p><b>LIST OF SATELLITES</b>
<p><b>Satellite number according to satellite information file:</b>
Specify the satellite numbers to be processed according to the satellite
information file. The example list shows different satellite numbers.

<p><i>Remark:</i>
The example list is not valid for all time intervals. The
PRN of the GPS and GLONASS satellites may change from time to time. Please
carefully check the satellite information file for the correct numbering.

<p><hr>

<p><b>QLRSUM 3: Outlier detection</b>

<a name="RESMAX" default="1.0"></a>
<p><b>EDITING LEVEL</b>
<p><b>Absolute maximum of the residuals:</b>
Specify a threshold for the observation residuals. If a residual exceeds this
threshold, an entry in the corresponding "Edit file" (panel 1) will be made
for this observation.

<a name="SIGMAX" default="1000.0"></a>
<p><b>Maximum overall sigma:</b>
Specify a sigma which the residual time series for a station / satellite 
should not exceed.

<a name="SIGFAC" default="1000.0"></a>
<p><b>Multiplication factor for overall sigma:</b>
Specify a factor for multiplying the overall sigma given above. If a residual
exceeds this threshold, an entry in the corresponding "Edit file" will be
made for this observation.

<p><i>Remark:</i>
Each pair of station and satellite is treated independently.

<p><i>Remark:</i>
By specifying a large multiplication factor, e.g. 1000, the outlier detection
is de facto switched off.

<br><br>

<a name="EDIT_1" default="1"></a>
<p><b>OUTLIER DETECTION</b>
<p><b>Edit only station/satellite with largest RMS:</b>
Only the station with the largest RMS will be checked for outliers according to
the editing criteria specified above. And only outliers of this station are
written to the corresponding "Edit file".

<a name="EDIT_2" default="0"></a>
<p><b>Edit all residuals according to editing criteria above:</b>
All stations are checked for outliers according to the editing criteria
specified above.

<br><br>

<a name="CHKNUM" default="0"></a>
<p><b>CHECK NUMBER OF OBSERVATIONS</b>
<p><b>Mark observations if number of observations too small:</b>
Mark this checkbox if you want to exclude stations with too few observations.
An entry will be made in the corresponding "Edit file" for each of these
observations.

<a name="MINOBS" default="10"></a>
<p><b>Minimum number of observations requested:</b>
Specify the minimum number of observations for a station (/satellite).
If less observations are available, an entry in the corresponding "Edit file"
will be made.

<a name="CHKNUM_1" default="1"></a>
<a name="CHKNUM_2" default="0"></a>
<p><b>Check number of observations:</b>
Select whether the minimum number of observations is requested <b>per station</b>
(computed as the sum over all satellites tracked by this station), or whether
the minimum number of observations is requested for each pair of <b>station and
satellite</b>.

<p><hr>

</body>
</html>
